# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: johnny-bates-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/1906-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1906 throughout the world.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/1906-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/1914-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1914 throughout the world.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] The **Baltimore Terrapins** were a team in the short-lived Federal League of professional baseball from 1914 to 1915.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Their brief existence led to litigation that led to an important legal precedent in baseball.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] The team played its home games at Terrapin Park.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Most of the professional baseball teams in Baltimore have been called the Orioles, in reference to the Baltimore oriole bird.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] There was already a minor league Baltimore Orioles, and the new Federal League club built their ballpark directly across the street from the Orioles park.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] The new club chose to call itself the Baltimore Terrapins, after the diamondback terrapin, the state reptile of Maryland.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] That nickname would later become primarily associated with the University of Maryland, College Park sports teams called the Maryland Terrapins.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore gathered for spring training in Southern Pines, North Carolina at the Southern Pines Golf Club, previously used by the Philadelphia Phillies in 1909 and 1910.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Terrapins manager Otto Knabe had played for these Phillies teams and trained in Southern Pines.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] While the 1914 team posted a respectable 84–70 record and finished only 4½ games out of first place under player-manager Otto Knabe, the team was less than successful at the box office, even though four of the eight teams in the league (Chicago, Brooklyn, Pittsburgh, and St.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) were competing with one and even two (Chicago and St.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) other major league teams in the same cities.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] In an attempt to turn this situation around and attract a marquee player to help them at the box office, the 1915 team recruited Chief Bender of the American League champion Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] The Athletics had sold off several future Hall-of-Famers like Eddie Plank, Eddie Collins and Frank "Home Run" Baker after being swept by the surprising Boston Braves in the 1914 World Series.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Bender had come off an impressive 17–3 season where he compiled seven shutouts and a 2.26 ERA in 1914.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] However, his 1915 season at Baltimore was a low point of his Hall of Fame career when he slumped to a 4–16 record, no shutouts, and a 3.99 ERA.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore's collapse to a 47–107 record, 40 games out of first, was overshadowed only by the collapse of Bender's former team who went from a 99–53 league championship season to a dismal 43–109 record, 58½ games out of first in 1915.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Bender and the Baltimore Terrapins never made a full recovery from 1915.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] The incident did show the Federal League could compete seriously with the National League and American League on a professional baseball level and led to the buy-out truce which ended the Federal League for good.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] However, the Baltimore team's owners were not offered a part in this buyout.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] When the Federal League started, the Terrapins severely cut into the minor league Baltimore Orioles' attendance, causing financial problems for the owner.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] As a result, several players, including the young left-handed pitcher Babe Ruth, were offered for sale to major league teams.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Ruth's contract was purchased by the Boston Red Sox, after being turned down by Connie Mack and the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] In 1914, Ruth began his career with the Red Sox of the rival American League.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] After the demise of the Federal League and the Terrapins, Baltimore would not see major league baseball again until 1954, when the former St.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Louis Browns moved into town and became the present-day Baltimore Orioles.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] As the Terrapins' owners were not offered any part of the buyout offer made to most Federal League teams by the American and National Leagues, they decided to sue, alleging that the buyout was in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] Supreme Court deciding that the scheduling and playing of "base ball games" did not constitute "interstate commerce" in any sense envisioned by the Framers of the United States Constitution; therefore, the Sherman Act and other federal laws and regulations did not apply to baseball.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] National League*, was not ultimately decided until 1922.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] The minor league Orioles moved into Terrapin Park, a wooden ballpark.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baltimore-terrapins] This move began a chain of events which would eventually lead to the return of major league baseball to Baltimore.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] A **base on balls** (**BB**), better known as a **walk**, occurs in baseball when a batter receives four pitches during a plate appearance that the umpire calls *balls*, and is in turn awarded first base without the possibility of being called out.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] The base on balls is defined in Section 2.00 of baseball's Official Rules, and further detail is given in 6.08(a).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Despite being known as a "walk", it is considered a faux pas for a professional player to actually walk to first base; the batter-runner and any advancing runners normally jog on such a play.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] The term "base on balls" distinguishes a walk from the other manners in which a batter can be awarded first base without liability to be put out (e.g., hit by pitch (HBP), catcher's interference).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Though a base on balls, catcher's interference, or a batter hit by a pitched ball all result in the batter (and possibly runners on base) being awarded a base, the term "walk" usually refers only to a base on balls, and not the other methods of reaching base without the bat touching the ball.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] An important difference is that for a hit batter or catcher's interference, the ball is dead and no one may advance unless forced; the ball is live after a walk (see below for details).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] A batter who draws a base on balls is commonly said to have been "walked" by the pitcher.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] When the batter is walked, runners advance one base without liability to be put out only if forced to vacate their base to allow the batter to take first base.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] If a batter draws a walk with the bases loaded, all preceding runners are forced to advance, including the runner on third base who is forced to home plate to score a run; when a run is forced on a walk, the batter is credited with a run batted in per rule 9.04.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Receiving a base on balls does not count as a hit or an at bat for a batter but does count as a time on base and a plate appearance.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Therefore, a base on balls does not affect a player's batting average, but it can increase his on-base percentage.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] A hit by pitch is not counted statistically as a walk, though the effect is mostly the same, with the batter receiving a free pass to first base.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] One exception is that on hit-by-pitch, the ball is dead, and any runners attempting to steal on the play must return to their original base unless forced to the next base anyway.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] When a walk occurs, the ball is still live: any runner not forced to advance may nevertheless attempt to advance at his own risk, which might occur on a steal play, passed ball, or wild pitch.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Also, because a ball is live when a base on balls occurs, runners on base forced to advance one base may attempt to advance beyond one base, at their own risk.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] The batter-runner himself may attempt to advance beyond first base, at his own risk.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Rule 6.08 addresses this matter as well.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] An attempt to advance an additional base beyond the base awarded might occur when ball four is a passed ball or a wild pitch.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] In early baseball, there was no concept of a "ball".
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] In 1869 the rule was modified so that only those baserunners forced to advance could advance.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] From 1871 through 1886, the batter was entitled to call "high" or "low", i.e. above or below the waist; a pitch which failed to conform was "unfair".
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Certain pitches were defined as automatic balls in 1872: any ball delivered over the batter's head, that hit the ground in front of home plate, was delivered to the opposite side from the batter, or came within one foot of him.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] In 1880, the National League changed the rules so that eight "unfair balls" instead of nine were required for a walk.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] In 1884, the National League changed the rules so that six balls were required for a walk.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] In 1886, the American Association changed the rules so that six balls instead of seven were required for a walk; however, the National League changed the rules so that seven balls were required for a walk instead of six.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] In 1887, the National League and American Association agreed to abide by some uniform rule changes, including, for the first time, a strike zone which defined balls and strikes by rule rather than the umpire's discretion, and decreased the number of balls required for a walk to five.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] In 1889, the National League and the American Association decreased the number of balls required for a walk to four.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] In 2017, Major League Baseball approved a rule change allowing for a batter to be walked intentionally by having the defending bench signal to the umpire.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] A subset of the base on balls, an intentional base on balls (IBB), or intentional walk, is when the defensive team intentionally issues a walk to the batter.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] In Major League Baseball and many amateur leagues, an intentional base on balls is signaled to the home plate umpire by the defensive team's manager holding up four fingers, at which point the batter is awarded first base without any further pitches being thrown.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] As with any other walk, an intentional walk entitles the batter to first base without liability to be put out, and entitles any runners to advance if forced.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Intentional walks are a strategic defensive maneuver, commonly done to bypass one hitter for one the defensive team believes is less likely to initiate a run-scoring play (e.g., a home run, sacrifice fly, or RBI base hit).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Teams also commonly use intentional walks to set up a double play or force out situation for the next batter.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Jimmie Foxx, Andre Thornton, Jeff Bagwell and Bryce Harper have each been walked six times during a major league regular season game.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] Among pitchers, Tommy Byrne and Bruno Haas both gave up 16 bases on balls in a game.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] On September 17, 1920, the Boston Red Sox drew 20 walks in a 12-inning game against the Detroit Tigers.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/base-on-balls] As of September 2024, this is the most walks drawn or allowed by a team in a single game in Major League history according to available data.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The **Boston Braves** were a Major League Baseball team that played in Boston for the National League from 1871 to 1952.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The team relocated to Milwaukee after the 1952 season, becoming the Milwaukee Braves, and subsequently moved to Atlanta in 1966.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] During its 82-year stay in Massachusetts, the franchise was known by various nicknames, including the **Red Stockings**, **Red Caps**, **Beaneaters**, **Rustlers**, **Bees**, and "Braves".
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Their longest-lasting nickname was inspired by Tamanend, a chief of the Lenni-Lenape in the Delaware Valley.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] While in Boston, the team won 10 National League pennants and a World Series championship in 1914 that came after a season in which the Braves were in last place as late as July 15—a turnaround that led to the nickname "Miracle Braves".
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] In 1948, the Braves reached the World Series largely as a result of their two dominant pitchers, Warren Spahn and Johnny Sain, who inspired the *Boston Post* slogan "Spahn and Sain and pray for rain." The Braves posted a losing record in all but 12 of the 38 seasons after their World Series win.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Boston franchise played at South End Grounds from 1871 to 1914 and at Braves Field from 1915 to 1952.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Braves Field is now Nickerson Field of Boston University.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The franchise, from Boston to Milwaukee to Atlanta, is the oldest continuously operating professional baseball franchise.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Boston Braves had an overall win–loss record of 5,118–5,598–138 (.478) during their 77-year major-league tenure in Boston.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Six former Boston Braves players have been elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Cincinnati Red Stockings, established in 1869 as the first openly all-professional baseball team, voted to dissolve after the 1870 season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Player-manager Harry Wright then went to Boston, Massachusetts—at the invitation of Boston businessman Ivers Whitney Adams—with brother George Wright and two other Cincinnati players joined the **Boston Red Stockings**, a charter member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] This team and its successors are the oldest continuously playing team in American professional sports.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Led by the Wright brothers, Barnes, and Spalding, the Red Stockings won four of the National Association's five championships.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The team became one of the National League's charter franchises in 1876, sometimes called the "**Red Caps**" (as a new Cincinnati Red Stockings club was another charter member).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Boston came to be called the **Beaneaters** by sportswriters in 1883, while retaining red as the team color.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Red Caps/Beaneaters won eight pennants during the 19th century.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Their manager was Frank Selee, the first manager not to double as a player as well.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The 1898 team finished 102–47, a club record for wins that would stand for almost a century.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] In 1894 the Braves became the first major league baseball team to wear letterforms on their uniform caps when they added a monogram-style device to their front.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] In 1897, the Beaneaters, as runner-up in the National League, took part in the 1897 Temple Cup championship series against the Baltimore Orioles, losing in five games.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] They only managed one winning season from 1900 to 1913, and lost 100 or more games six times.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] In 1907, the renamed Doves (temporarily) eliminated the red from their stockings because their manager thought the red dye could cause wounds to become infected (as noted in *The Sporting News Baseball Guide* during the 1940s when each team's entry had a history of its nickname(s).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] See details in History of baseball team nicknames).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The American League club's owner, Charles Taylor, changed his team's name to the Red Sox in place of the "Americans".
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] When George and John Dovey acquired the club in 1907, the team was named the **Doves**; when purchased by William Hepburn Russell in 1911 reporters tried out **Rustlers.** The team adopted an official name, the **Braves**, for the first time in 1912.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Their owner, James Gaffney, a member of New York City's Tammany Hall, tributed the team to Tamanend, "The Patron Saint of America," with the name and his image as the logo.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Two years later, the Braves put together one of the most memorable seasons in baseball history.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] After a dismal 4–18 start, the Braves seemed to be on pace for a last place finish.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] On July 4, 1914, the Braves lost both games of a doubleheader to the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The consecutive losses put their record at 26–40 and the Braves were in last place, 15 games behind the league-leading New York Giants, who had won the previous three league pennants.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] After a day off, the Braves put together a hot streak, and from July 6 through September 5, the Braves won 41 games against only 12 losses.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] On September 7 and 8, the Braves took 2 of 3 from the New York Giants and moved into first place.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Braves tore through September and early October, closing with 25 wins against 6 losses, while the Giants went 16–16.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] They are the only team to win a pennant after being in last place on the Fourth of July.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] They were in last place as late as July 18, but were close to the pack, moving into fourth on July 21 and second place on August 12.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Despite their comeback, the Braves entered the World Series as a heavy underdog to Connie Mack's Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Nevertheless, the Braves swept the Athletics—the first unqualified sweep in the young history of the modern World Series (the 1907 World Series had one tied game)—to win the world championship.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Meanwhile, former Chicago Cubs infielder Johnny Evers, in his second season with the Braves, won the Chalmers Award.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Braves played the World Series (as well as the last few weeks of the 1914 regular season) at Fenway Park, since their normal home, the South End Grounds, was too small.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] However, the Braves' success inspired owner Gaffney to build a modern park, Braves Field, which opened in August 1915.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] It was the largest park in the majors at the time, with 40,000 seats and also a very spacious outfield.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The park was novel for its time; public transportation brought fans right into the park.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] After contending for most of 1915 and 1916, the Braves spent much of the next 19 years in mediocrity, during which they posted only three winning seasons (1921, 1933, and 1934).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The lone highlight of those years came when Giants' attorney Emil Fuchs bought the team in 1923 to bring his longtime friend, pitching great Christy Mathewson, back into the game.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Although original plans called for Mathewson to be the principal owner, he had never recovered from tuberculosis that he had contracted after being gassed during World War I.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] By the end of the 1923 season, it was obvious Mathewson could not continue even in a reduced role, and he would die two years later, with the result that Fuchs was permanently given the presidency.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] In 1928, the Braves traded for Hall of Famer Rogers Hornsby who had a very productive year in his only season with Boston.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] He batted .387 to win his seventh and final batting championship.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Fuchs was committed to building a winner, but the damage from the years before his arrival took some time to overcome.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Braves finally managed to compete in 1933 and 1934 under manager Bill McKechnie, but Fuchs' revenue was severely depleted due to the Great Depression.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Looking for a way to get more supporters and more money, Fuchs worked out a deal with the New York Yankees to acquire Babe Ruth, who had, coincidentally, started his career with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Fuchs named Ruth vice president and assistant manager of the Braves, and promised him a share of team profits.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] He was also to be consulted on all player transactions.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Fuchs even suggested that Ruth, who had long had his heart set on managing, could take over as manager once McKechnie stepped down—perhaps as early as 1936.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] At first, it looked like Ruth was the final piece the team needed in 1935.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] On opening day, he had a hand in all of the Braves' runs in a 4–2 win over the Giants.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Opening Day proved to be the only time the Braves were over .500 all year.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] A 4–20 May ended any realistic chance of contention.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] At the same time, it became apparent that Ruth was finished even as a part-time player.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] While his high living of previous years had begun catching up with him a year earlier, his conditioning rapidly declined in the first month of 1935.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] While he was still able to hit at first, he could do little else.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] He could no longer run, and his fielding was so terrible that three of the Braves' pitchers threatened to go on strike if Ruth were in the lineup.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Ruth soon discovered that he was vice president and assistant manager in name only, and Fuchs' promise of a share of team profits was hot air.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] In fact, Ruth discovered that Fuchs expected him to invest some of *his* money in the team.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Seeing a franchise in complete disarray, Ruth retired on June 1, only six days after he clouted what turned out to be the last three home runs of his career, in what remains one of the most memorable afternoons in baseball history.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] He had wanted to quit as early as May 12, but Fuchs wanted him to hang on so he could play in every National League park.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] By this time, the Braves were 9–27, their season all but over.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] They ultimately finished 38–115, easily the worst season in franchise history.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Their .248 winning percentage is tied for the seventh-worst in baseball history, and the sixth-worst in National League history.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] It is the second-worst in modern baseball history (behind only the 1916 Philadelphia Athletics), and the worst in modern National League history.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Insolvent like his team, Fuchs was forced to give up control of the Braves in August 1935.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The principal financial backer for the team, Charles F.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Adams, was banned by Commissioner Landis from taking control of the team because Adams owned Suffolk Downs race track.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Quinn did not care for the Braves name, possibly because it was linked to former owner Gaffney and to New York's Tammany Hall politics and launched a contest for the general public with the regional sportswriters being the judges.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Among 13,000 votes of 1,327 potential names, the team was renamed to the **Boston Bees** Keeping up with the Bees theme, Braves Field became nicknamed the Bee Hive.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] This did little to change the team's fortunes.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] After five uneven years, a new owner, construction magnate Lou Perini, changed the nickname back to the Braves.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] In 1948, the team won the National League pennant by capturing 91 games to finish 61⁄2 places ahead of the second–place St.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] They also attracted 1,455,439 fans to Braves Field, the third-largest gate in the National League and a high-water mark for the team's stay in Boston.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The pitching staff was anchored by Hall of Famer Warren Spahn and Johnny Sain, who won 39 games between them.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The poem received such a wide audience that the sentiment, usually now paraphrased as "Spahn, Sain, then pray for rain" or "Spahn, Sain and two days of rain", entered the baseball vocabulary.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Ironically, in the 1948 season, the Braves actually had a better record in games that Spahn and Sain *did not* start than in games they did.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Braves lost the 1948 World Series in six games to the Cleveland Indians (who had beaten the Red Sox in a tie-breaker game to spoil an all-Boston World Series).
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] This turned out to be the Braves' last hurrah in Boston.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Acquired earlier by trade from the Brooklyn Dodgers, on April 18, 1950, Sam "Jet" Jethroe was added to the Boston Braves roster.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Dodgers had another young CF in Duke Snider rising in their system, resulting in the trade to the Braves.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Going on to be named National League Rookie of the Year at age 32, Jethroe broke the color barrier with Boston.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] In 1950, Jethroe hit .273 with 100 runs, 18 home runs and 58 RBI.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] His 35 stolen bases led the National League, a feat he would duplicate in 1951.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] While in Boston, Jethroe was a roommate of Chuck Cooper, of the Boston Celtics who was the first African-American player drafted by an NBA team.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] A former Negro leagues star and military veteran, Jethroe remains the oldest player to have won Rookie of the Year honors.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Amid four mediocre seasons after 1948, attendance steadily dwindled, even though Braves Field had the reputation of being more family friendly than Fenway.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] For a half century, the major leagues had not had a single franchise move.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Braves played their last home game in Boston on September 21, 1952, losing to the Brooklyn Dodgers 8–2 before 8,822 at Braves Field; the home attendance for the 1952 season was under 282,000.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] On March 13, 1953, owner Lou Perini said that he would seek permission from the National League to move the Braves to Milwaukee, Wisconsin.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] After the franchise's long history in Boston, the day became known as "Black Friday" in the city as fans mourned the team's exit after eight decades.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Perini, however, pointed to dwindling attendance as the main reason for the move.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] He also announced that he had recently bought out his original partners.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] He announced Milwaukee as that was where the Braves had their top farm club, the Brewers.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Milwaukee had long been a possible target for moving.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Louis Browns there earlier the same year (Milwaukee was the original home of that franchise), but his proposal had been voted down by the other American League owners.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Going into spring training in 1953, it appeared that the Braves would play another year in Boston unless the National League gave permission for the move.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] After a 31⁄2-hour meeting at the Vinoy Park Hotel in St.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] Petersburg, Florida, league approval was granted after Perini promised not to sell the team.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] During a game against the New York Yankees on March 18, the sale was announced final and that the team would move to Milwaukee, immediately.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The All-Star Game had been scheduled for Braves Field.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] It was moved to Crosley Field and hosted by the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Braves franchise moved their triple-A Brewers from Milwaukee to Toledo, Ohio.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] After the Braves moved to Milwaukee in 1953, the Braves Field site was sold to Boston University and reconstructed as Nickerson Field, the home of many Boston University teams.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/boston-beaneaters] The Braves Field scoreboard was sold to the Kansas City A's and used at Municipal Stadium; the A's moved to Oakland after the 1967 season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] He entered professional baseball with the 1905 Sharon Steels, a new team in the Ohio-Pennsylvania League.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] Bates made his major league debut in April 1906 with the Boston Beaneaters.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] He hit a home run in that first major league game, one of only six home runs he hit that season and one of 25 major league home runs in his career.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] He became a regular outfielder for Boston right away, playing 140 games that first season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] On April 26, 1907, Bates hit for the cycle at Washington Park in Brooklyn.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] He was the Boston leadoff hitter, but until that game he had gotten only 8 hits in 48 at bats in the 1907 season.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] He hit a triple in the first at bat of the game, an infield single in the third inning, a double in the fifth inning, and a home run in the seventh inning.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] Bates was the third player in franchise history to hit for the cycle.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] In July 1909, Bates was hitting .288, much higher than his previous season batting averages, when Boston traded him to the Philadelphia Phillies in a multiplayer deal.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] He then hit .293 for the Phillies that year.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] Bates was involved in another multiplayer trade after 1910 season, this time to the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] He had one of his best seasons with the 1911 Reds.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] He hit .292 that year and, largely because his walk total ballooned to 103, he had an on base percentage of .415.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] His last major league season was 1914, which he split between the Reds, the Chicago Cubs, and the Baltimore Terrapins of the Federal League.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] In 1154 games, Bates recorded 1087 hits, 25 home runs and 417 RBI with a .278 batting average.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] From 1915 to 1918, Bates returned to the minor leagues, playing mostly in the International League.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] Bates was a glassworker after retiring from baseball, and then he became a deputy sheriff for Jefferson County, Ohio.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] His stepson, Robert Dobbie Bates, was the county sheriff there in the late 1930s and 1940s.
[src:johnny-bates-baseball/johnny-bates-baseball] In 1949, Bates had a heart attack while he was shoveling snow, and he died ten days later in his native Steubenville.
